### History

*James City County on an 1895 map*

*This section incorporates text from the [1911 edition of the Encyclopædia Britannica](/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica), which is in the [public domain](/Public_domain).*

### 17th and 18th centuries

#### Proprietary colony

*Main article: [History of the Jamestown Settlement (1607-1699)](/History_of_the_Jamestown_Settlement_(1607-1699))*

The early 17th century was a rather ambitious, if not entirely well-conceived, period for English imperial expansion. The [Virginia Company of London](/Virginia_Company_of_London), a joint-stock company operating under a proprietorship (a charter granted by the Crown), was given the rather daunting task by King [James I of England](/James_I_of_England) to establish a viable colony in the vast, untamed wilderness known loosely as Virginia. This wasn't merely an act of adventurous exploration; England, having recently concluded hostilities with Spain, was desperately seeking both capital funds to replenish its coffers and a steady stream of income in the form of royalties from colonial ventures. It was a gamble, to be sure, driven by economic necessity and a touch of national pride.

In December 1606, three small ships — the *Susan Constant*, the *Godspeed*, and the *Discovery* — laden with a mix of hopeful, desperate, and utterly unprepared colonists, set sail from England. Under the command of the seasoned Captain [Christopher Newport](/Christopher_Newport), they navigated the treacherous Atlantic, eventually making landfall in the New World at [Cape Henry](/Cape_Henry). Their directive was clear: establish a settlement well inland, away from the immediate threat of Spanish warships lurking off the coast. After some initial exploration, they selected a site approximately 40 miles (64 km) inland from the coast, along a broad river they christened the [James River](/James_River_(Virginia)), hoping its depth and relative seclusion would offer a measure of protection from maritime attacks by other European powers. Thus, in May 1607, [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) was established, a rather crude and vulnerable outpost in the new [Colony of Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia).

The initial five years of the settlement were, to put it mildly, a catastrophic exercise in human folly and resilience. The majority of the early colonists perished, succumbing to disease, starvation, and conflicts with the indigenous [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) tribes. It was a brutal initiation into the realities of the New World. Salvation, or at least solvency, arrived in 1612 when the colonist [John Rolfe](/John_Rolfe) managed to successfully cultivate imported strains of [tobacco](/Tobacco), specifically a sweeter variety from Trinidad, which quickly found favor in the European market. This discovery transformed the fledgling colony's prospects, providing the much-needed [cash crop](/Cash_crop) that would fuel its growth, albeit with profound social and economic consequences.

By 1619, the [Virginia Company of London](/Virginia_Company_of_London), under the fresh leadership of [Sir Edwin Sandys](/Edwin_Sandys_(American_colonist)), recognized the desperate need for reform. A series of fundamental changes were instituted, designed to invigorate investment and entice more settlers from [England](/England) to brave the perils of colonial life. Among these reforms, and arguably the most far-reaching in its historical impact, was the establishment of what would become the [House of Burgesses](/House_of_Burgesses). This pioneering assembly represented the first instance of a representative legislative body in any European settlement in North America, a direct ancestor to today's [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly). It was first convened by the Royal Governor, [Sir George Yeardley](/George_Yeardley), at the now-famous [Flowerdew Hundred Plantation](/Flowerdew_Hundred_Plantation). The year 1619 also saw the administrative reorganization of the colony: the existing [plantations](/Plantations_in_the_American_South) and settled areas were divided into four expansive "incorporations" or "citties," as they were then known. These territorial divisions, stretching from east to west, were [Elizabeth Cittie](/Elizabeth_City_(Virginia_Company)) (initially known as Kecoughtan), [James Cittie](/James_City_(Virginia_Company)), [Charles Cittie](/Charles_City_(Virginia_Company)), and [Henrico Cittie](/Henrico_City_(Virginia_Company)). Each "cittie" encompassed an impressively vast geographical area, for instance, [Elizabeth Cittie](/Elizabeth_City_(Virginia_Company)) extended beyond land on both sides of the [James River](/James_River_(Virginia)) to include much of what is now [South Hampton Roads](/South_Hampton_Roads) and even Virginia's [Eastern Shore](/Eastern_Shore_of_Virginia).

The Virginia Company's "James Cittie," the administrative precursor to the modern county, was particularly extensive. It stretched across the breadth of the [Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula), reaching as far north as the [York River](/York_River_(Virginia)), and crucially, it encompassed the very seat of government for the entire colony at [Jamestown Island](/Jamestown_Island). In a rather pragmatic move dictated by the realities of colonial commerce, each of these four original citties was designed to extend across the [James River](/James_River_(Virginia)), which served as the primary thoroughfare for trade and transportation, thus including land on both the north and south shores. These incentives introduced in 1619 proved effective, leading to a rapid proliferation of new developments, each typically referred to as a "[hundred](/Hundred_(county_subdivision))," dotting the landscape.

#### Wolstenholme Towne, Carter's Grove Plantation

Around this same dynamic period, a new fortified settlement, [Wolstenholme Towne](/Wolstenholme_Towne), began to take shape downriver from the main Jamestown site. Located in what is now the southeastern quadrant of James City County, near the contemporary community of [Grove](/Grove,_Virginia), this town was strategically positioned close to the [James River](/James_River_(Virginia)) and just east of where Grove Creek joined the larger waterway. It was established on a substantial land grant known as [Martin's Hundred](/Martin%27s_Hundred), an investment venture backed by the Martin's Hundred Society in England. The town itself was named in honor of [Sir John Wolstenholme, 1st Baronet](/Sir_John_Wolstenholme,_1st_Baronet), a prominent principal among those investors. However, this nascent community was to suffer a devastating blow. Its population was severely decimated during the horrific [Indian massacre of 1622](/Indian_massacre_of_1622), an event that saw many men, women, and children either brutally killed or abducted. While the survivors valiantly attempted to rebuild, [Wolstenholme Towne](/Wolstenholme_Towne) ultimately proved unsustainable, eventually being abandoned around 1643. Its location, like so many early colonial endeavors, faded from collective memory, becoming one of the many [lost towns of Virginia](/Former_counties,_cities,_and_towns_of_Virginia).

Over a century later, the land that once held [Wolstenholme Towne](/Wolstenholme_Towne) had been absorbed into the expansive [Carter's Grove Plantation](/Carter%27s_Grove_Plantation). This grand manor house, a marvel of Georgian architecture, was constructed around 1753 by the grandson of [Robert "King" Carter](/Robert_Carter_I) of [Corotoman](/Corotoman), a man who had amassed immense wealth as a planter and even served a stint as Virginia's acting governor. The historical irony of one lost settlement resting beneath the grounds of another, later, prominent estate is not lost on those who appreciate the layers of history. Another two centuries passed before the long-forgotten site of [Wolstenholme Towne](/Wolstenholme_Towne) was dramatically rediscovered in 1976. This archaeological triumph occurred during a meticulous excavation overseen by the renowned historical archaeologist [Ivor Noel Hume](/Ivor_Noel_Hume), a discovery made possible after the [Carter's Grove Plantation](/Carter%27s_Grove_Plantation) property came under the stewardship of the [Colonial Williamsburg Foundation](/Colonial_Williamsburg_Foundation). It seems some secrets, no matter how deeply buried, eventually surface.

#### Royal colony, creation of shires (counties)

*James City County sign on [U.S. Route 60](/U.S._Route_60_in_Virginia) entering [Grove](/Grove,_Virginia) from east at [Skiffe's Creek](/Skiffe%27s_Creek). This border with the former [Warwick County](/Warwick_County,_Virginia) was established in 1634 by order of King Charles I of England (Warwick County became part of the [City of Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia) in 1958).*

The grand experiment of the privately owned [Virginia Company](/Virginia_Company) ultimately faltered, and its charter was revoked by the Crown in 1624. This transition marked a significant shift: Virginia ceased to be a speculative venture and was formally established as a [royal colony](/Royal_colony), directly governed by the English monarchy. A decade later, in 1634, demonstrating an enduring penchant for administrative order, the English Crown initiated the creation of eight distinct [shires](/Shires_of_Virginia) (which are, in essence, [counties](/County_(United_States))) within the newly designated royal colony. At this point, the total population of European inhabitants hovered around a modest 5,000. [James City Shire](/James_City_Shire), the direct ancestor of the modern county, alongside the [James River](/James_River_(Virginia)) and the settlement of [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) that had been named earlier, all derived their names from King [James I](/James_I_of_England), the father of the reigning monarch, [Charles I](/Charles_I_of_England). It's a rather predictable naming convention, if you ask me. Sometime between 1642 and 1643, the appellation of [James City Shire](/James_City_Shire) was formally updated to [James City County](/James_City_County), a name that has, against all odds, stuck for centuries.

#### Middle Plantation, Williamsburg, Green Spring

Perched on a strategically elevated ridge, roughly midway across the breadth of the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula), [Middle Plantation](/Middle_Plantation_(Virginia)) was founded in 1632. Its initial purpose was grimly practical: to serve as a fortress, a bulwark in the relentless and often brutal conflicts with the various [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) tribes. By 1634, a substantial palisade, a defensive barrier of sharpened logs, had been meticulously constructed, stretching across the entire peninsula with [Middle Plantation](/Middle_Plantation_(Virginia)) positioned squarely at its center. This formidable fortification was designed to protect the more settled lower peninsula to the east from further incursions and attacks.

The strategic importance of [Middle Plantation](/Middle_Plantation_(Virginia)) and, by extension, [James City County](/James_City_County), was further cemented in 1693 with its selection as the site for the newly chartered [College of William and Mary](/College_of_William_and_Mary), a prestigious institution of higher learning that would profoundly shape the intellectual and political landscape of the colony. Just a few years later, following yet another destructive fire that ravaged [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) in 1698, the capital of the [Virginia Colony](/Virginia_Colony) was officially relocated to [Middle Plantation](/Middle_Plantation_(Virginia)) in 1699. This move signaled a definitive shift in power and influence. Shortly thereafter, in an act of deference to the reigning monarch, [Middle Plantation](/Middle_Plantation_(Virginia)) was rather predictably renamed [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia), in honor of King [William III of England](/William_III_of_England). However, even capitals are not immune to the winds of change. At the very outset of the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution) in 1780, the capital was once again moved, this time further inland to [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia), a more defensible position away from potential British naval assaults. The county also bore witness to the [Battle of Green Spring](/Battle_of_Green_Spring), a significant engagement fought on its soil just a short time before the pivotal British surrender at Yorktown, effectively sealing the fate of the war. Notably, [Green Spring Plantation](/Green_Spring_Plantation) itself was the former residence of the Royal Governor [William Berkeley](/William_Berkeley_(governor)), further imbuing the area with layers of historical significance.

### 19th and 20th centuries

The 19th and 20th centuries brought their own share of historical drama and transformative development to [James City County](/James_City_County).

During the brutal crucible of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War), the county became a theater of conflict. Specifically, the [Battle of Williamsburg](/Battle_of_Williamsburg) raged across parts of both York and [James City County](/James_City_County) in 1862, a key engagement within the larger [Peninsula Campaign](/Peninsula_Campaign) launched by Union forces to capture the Confederate capital of [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia). Today, faint but discernible earthworks still bear silent witness to those desperate struggles, particularly at the site of the Confederate [Fort Magruder](/Fort_Magruder). Following the cessation of hostilities, a new kind of conquest began: economic expansion. The visionary industrialist [Collis P. Huntington](/Collis_P._Huntington) extended the tracks of the new [Chesapeake and Ohio Railway](/Chesapeake_and_Ohio_Railway) directly through the county. His ambition was to connect the burgeoning western coalfields to the new [coal piers](/Coal_pier) he had meticulously constructed at [Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia), strategically located on the deep waters of [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads). This railway brought with it a network of new lifeblood, establishing vital railroad stations (listed from west to east) at Diascund, [Toano](/Toano,_Virginia), [Vaiden's Crossing](/Norge,_Virginia) (later known as Norge), [Kelton](/Kelton,_Virginia), Ewell, [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia), and [Grove](/Grove,_Virginia). For a brief, rather chaotic period, the temporary tracks initially laid through [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) actually ran straight down the middle of the historic Duke of Gloucester Street, a testament to the raw, unpolished nature of progress at the time.

A constitutional shift in Virginia in 1871 had profound implications for municipal governance. This change ultimately led to [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia)'s formal designation as an [independent city](/Independent_city_(United_States)) in 1884, separating it politically from [James City County](/James_City_County). Despite this administrative divorce, the two entities have maintained a pragmatic, if somewhat unusual, symbiosis. They continue to share a combined public school system, judicial courts, and several constitutional officers, a collaboration that speaks to their interwoven destinies.

The early 20th century heralded a new era, one focused on the painstaking work of preservation and restoration. These efforts, driven by a burgeoning appreciation for the region's unparalleled historical significance, sparked a dramatic increase in tourism to the county and its surrounding areas. A constellation of attractions began to take shape, meticulously developed to captivate visitors with glimpses into the past. These included the immersive living history museum of [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg), the interpretive exhibits of the [Jamestown Settlement](/Jamestown_Settlement), the scenic drive of the [Colonial Parkway](/Colonial_Parkway), the elegant [Carter's Grove Plantation](/Carter%27s_Grove_Plantation), and the modern recreational thrills of [Busch Gardens Williamsburg](/Busch_Gardens_Williamsburg). This diverse array of offerings cemented the region's status as a premier tourist destination, blending education with entertainment.

#### Colonial Williamsburg

Perhaps the most iconic and transformative local development of the 20th century, profoundly impacting [James City County](/James_City_County) even from beyond its strict borders, was the monumental Restoration and subsequent development of [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg). This ambitious project was born from the singular vision of an Episcopal priest, W.A.R. Goodwin, whose fervent belief in the power of history inspired a monumental undertaking. It received its initial, and indeed foundational, funding from the formidable heir to the [Standard Oil](/Standard_Oil) fortune, [John D. Rockefeller Jr.](/John_D._Rockefeller_Jr.), and his equally influential wife, [Abby Aldrich Rockefeller](/Abby_Aldrich_Rockefeller). Together, their patronage transformed [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) (or "CW," as it is affectionately, and efficiently, known locally) into a world-class attraction, a meticulously recreated 18th-century capital unlike any other. It stands as a testament to the power of capital, meticulously applied.

*Main article: [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg)*

While the primary "Historic Area" of [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) is geographically situated within the city limits of [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) itself, and thus technically outside [James City County](/James_City_County), the [Colonial Williamsburg Foundation](/Colonial_Williamsburg_Foundation) strategically acquired vast tracts of land throughout the entire surrounding area in its earliest developmental phases. This acquisition focused notably on the expansive territories to the north and east of the Historic District. The primary motivation behind this extensive land procurement was a desire to meticulously preserve the visual integrity of the surrounding landscape, thereby facilitating an immersive visitor experience. The goal was to allow a visitor to genuinely feel transported to the late 18th century, with the surrounding environment carefully curated to avoid jarring modern intrusions.

The design of the entrance roadways leading into the Historic Area was executed with an almost obsessive level of care. Even in contemporary times, the pathways originating from the scenic [Colonial Parkway](/Colonial_Parkway) and from the strategically relocated [U.S. Route 60](/U.S._Route_60_in_Virginia) at Bypass Road and North Henry Street remain conspicuously devoid of commercial development. This commitment to an untouched vista was further extended along [U.S. Route 132](/Route_132_(Virginia)) in [York County](/York_County,_Virginia) to the new thoroughfare when [Route 143](/Route_143_(Virginia)) was constructed as the [Merrimack Trail](/Merrimack_Trail) (originally designated as State Route 168) in the 1930s. Even when the massive infrastructure project of [Interstate 64](/Interstate_64_in_Virginia) was planned and subsequently built in the 1960s and early 1970s, the additional land along [Route 143](/Route_143_(Virginia)) from the specifically designated "Colonial Williamsburg" exit was similarly shielded from any form of commercial encroachment. Consequently, even today, a visitor traveling several miles to reach the Visitor's Center will encounter no commercial properties, a remarkable feat considering the immense value of such real estate.

Among the significant landholdings to the immediate east of the Historic Area, within [James City County](/James_City_County), was a vast tract historically known as the [Kingsmill Plantation](/Kingsmill,_Virginia) property. This estate was bisected by the ancient [Quarterpath Road](/Quarterpath_Road), a route dating back to the 17th century that once connected [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) directly to the [James River](/James_River_(Virginia)) at Burwell's Landing. While the original manor house, constructed in the 1730s, tragically burned in 1843, several resilient brick dependencies survived and continue to stand into the 21st century, silent sentinels of a bygone era. Immediately adjacent to the east of the [Kingsmill](/Kingsmill,_Virginia) tract lay [Carter's Grove Plantation](/Carter%27s_Grove_Plantation), a grand estate initially developed by a grandson of the formidable Royal Governor [Robert "King" Carter](/Robert_Carter_I). Over a span of more than 200 years, this property passed through a succession of owners, each leaving their mark through various modifications and additions. Then, in the 1960s, following the passing of its last resident, Ms. Molly McRae, [Carter's Grove Plantation](/Carter%27s_Grove_Plantation) came under the control of the Rockefeller Foundation, which subsequently gifted it to [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg). At that specific point in the mid-1960s, the landholdings of [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) stretched impressively from the Historic District all the way to [Skiffe's Creek](/Skiffe%27s_Creek), bordering [Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia) near [Lee Hall](/Lee_Hall,_Virginia).

(It's worth noting that [Carter's Grove](/Carter%27s_Grove), situated approximately 8 miles (13 km) from the main Historic Area, was operated as a satellite facility by [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) for a significant period, hosting several important educational and interpretive programs. However, this arrangement concluded in 2003. Subsequently, most of these programs were strategically relocated to be in closer proximity to the main Historic Area. The property itself was eventually sold in 2007, but with stringent restrictive and conservation covenants meticulously put in place to ensure its enduring protection. For a more exhaustive account, one might consult the separate article dedicated to [Carter's Grove](/Carter%E2%80%99s_Grove)).

#### Anheuser-Busch

*One of the famous [Clydesdale horses](/Clydesdale_(horse)) is seen at the [Busch Gardens Williamsburg](/Busch_Gardens_Williamsburg) theme park, part of a massive [Anheuser-Busch](/Anheuser-Busch) development in James City County which also includes a brewery, office park, and the [Kingsmill Resort](/Kingsmill,_Virginia) located east of Williamsburg just west of [Grove](/Grove,_Virginia).*

In the latter half of the 20th century, a different kind of development began to stir in [James City County](/James_City_County), far removed from the carefully preserved sight paths of [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg). The expansive, largely vacant land east of town, which had been owned by the [Colonial Williamsburg Foundation](/Colonial_Williamsburg_Foundation) and was locally known as the [Kingsmill](/Kingsmill,_Virginia) tract, had remained unproductive for both the Foundation and the wider community for a considerable time. This stagnant situation dramatically changed in the early 1970s, thanks to the astute leadership of CW Chairman [Winthrop Rockefeller](/Winthrop_Rockefeller).

Rockefeller, himself a son of the influential Abby and [John D. Rockefeller Jr.](/John_D._Rockefeller_Jr.), was a frequent visitor to the area and harbored a particular fondness for [Carter's Grove](/Carter%E2%80%99s_Grove) in the late 1960s. Beyond his philanthropic and historical interests, he also served as the Governor of the State of [Arkansas](/Arkansas), placing him in a unique position to connect with other prominent figures. It was through these connections that he became aware of the expansion ambitions of his St. Louis-based neighbor, [August Anheuser Busch Jr.](/Gussie_Busch), the formidable head of [Anheuser-Busch](/Anheuser-Busch) (AB). Busch, a shrewd businessman and a master of promotion, had, in the 1930s, famously originated the use of the now-iconic [Clydesdale](/Clydesdale_(breed)) team as a highly effective company logo.

In 1959, the [Anheuser-Busch](/Anheuser-Busch) company had already ventured into the realm of entertainment, opening what is now recognized as a pioneering [theme park](/Theme_park) in [Tampa, Florida](/Tampa,_Florida), then simply known as "Busch Gardens." This venture was remarkably visionary, predating the massive [Walt Disney World](/Walt_Disney_World) development nearby by several years, and today it thrives as [Busch Gardens Tampa Bay](/Busch_Gardens_Tampa_Bay). It seems Busch had a knack for anticipating future trends in leisure and entertainment.

While the intricate details of their negotiations have, predictably, never been widely publicized, by the time "Win" Rockefeller and "Gussie" Busch concluded their discussions and formalized their agreement, the Williamsburg area was on the cusp of its most significant transformation since the Restoration of [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) had commenced four decades earlier. The overarching goals of this ambitious collaboration were multifaceted: to complement the existing historical attractions of [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) and, crucially, to provide a substantial boost to the local economy, creating jobs and injecting new dynamism into the region.

The vast tract of land, primarily comprising the [Kingsmill](/Kingsmill,_Virginia) property, was formally sold by the [Colonial Williamsburg Foundation](/Colonial_Williamsburg_Foundation) to [Anheuser-Busch](/Anheuser-Busch) (AB) for a meticulously planned series of developments. The scale of AB's investment was truly immense, encompassing the construction of a large-scale brewery, the thrilling [Busch Gardens Williamsburg](/Busch_Gardens_Williamsburg) [theme park](/Theme_park), the elegant [Kingsmill](/Kingsmill,_Virginia) planned resort community, and McLaws Circle, a modern office park designed to attract new businesses. In a significant act of corporate philanthropy, a 60-acre (240,000 m²) portion of this land was generously donated by [Anheuser-Busch](/Anheuser-Busch) in the late 1960s to facilitate the development of the [James City County](/James_City_County) office complex. This strategic development transformed the economic landscape of the county.

Today, [Anheuser-Busch](/Anheuser-Busch) and its associated entities, born from that ambitious development plan, collectively represent the area's largest employment base, impressively surpassing both [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) and the various local military installations. In 2008, [Anheuser-Busch](/Anheuser-Busch) proudly held the distinction of being the world's second-largest brewer, a testament to the immense success of its operations, much of which is rooted in this significant investment in [James City County](/James_City_County).

### 21st century

As the calendar turned to the 21st century, the spirit of discovery continued to thrive in [James City County](/James_City_County). New [archaeological](/Archaeological) investigations commenced at [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) and the nearby [Green Spring Plantation](/Green_Spring_Plantation), driven by the tantalizing premise of uncovering fresh historical revelations. Both sites hold a particular allure for archaeologists precisely because of the fortunate absence of significant modern development after the mid-19th century, leaving their historical layers largely undisturbed and ripe for exploration. It's almost as if the past decided to wait patiently for us to catch up.

The site of [Wolstenholme Towne](/Wolstenholme_Towne), nestled within the [Carter's Grove](/Carter%E2%80%99s_Grove) property, remains a protected treasure. When the property was sold in 2007, stringent covenants were put in place, ensuring its preservation and safeguarding its potential for future archaeological activity. The ground beneath our feet, it seems, still holds countless stories, waiting for the right moment, and the right tools, to be unearthed.

---

### Geography

According to the always precise, if somewhat dry, data provided by the [U.S. Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), [James City County](/James_City_County) encompasses a total area of 179 square miles (460 km²). Of this total, a substantial 142 square miles (370 km²) constitute land, while the remaining 37 square miles (96 km²) are composed of water, accounting for a significant 20.5% of its overall footprint. The county's own GIS office offers an even more granular measurement, specifying the land area as 115,011.9 acres (46,543.7 ha). It's a rather respectable piece of the planet, if one is inclined to measure such things.

